spanGrp.span: The elders told me; they told me that they all came from a place called China Kicha.
Sigeglö-wa të yís ĩã í paga-l (_) të yís ĩã í she jie-wa kable beteu rö kã' kié China Kicha
My grandma, my mom came from China Kicha;
Es mamita es mina-wa je beteu rö China Kicha wa
that China Kicha is located in the Perez Zeledon area.
Je China Kicha jata-nã rö Perez Seledon jamĩ gataga
My grandpa is Indian; he is from our land, which is located in the Talamanca area.
Es tatiga je rö sa kã' wak je rö sa kã' ska Je kã' jata-nã komĩ kã' kié Talamanka (_)
My grandpa came from there and married my grandma in China Kicha.
(_) je-wa es tatiga beteu je ñã jula gugá es mamita mẽ China Kicha wa
They came to this place called Ujarraz.
Je nẽ beteu ji Ujarras kã' kie jegepi
In our language… in Spanish it is called Ujarraz; in our language it is called Sök.
se je ktö' wa kã' kwãwã mẽ ji (_) sikwa ktö' wa kie Ujarras
in our language it is called Sök.
Se je ktö' wa je kie rö Sök
The other people call us ‘[people] from Sök.
Pe kwãwã të se je kie rö Sök-wa
They tell me that once they got to Ujarraz to this savannah, there were lots of trees, nances, espavels, white cane, and a tree called kõsklö.

Jie-wa të yís ĩã í page jirpa í beteu í (_) Ujarras wa tara ji Sök kenẽgla kã' klabe bigögle je rö ka (r) kal ebö kal kié be'k kal kié kitá kal kié (r) kal kié juká rö kal kié jiebi tsõta kié kõ'sklö'
There were lots of deer, and a lot of food and meat to eat. There was a lot of meat in the bush, not like now that we have to buy everything with money.
Je tsõ tã'ĩ ji kã' inga Sök ebö jiebi tã'ĩ mulurbe tsõ yeké tsõ ña-nã yeké (r) yeké tsõ kata-nã yeké tsõ jiebi kã' dekĩ jãrga Ka rö jira ñãgepi se jenã kable tũã rö tõ'-le nãglö wa
Long ago, there was that on this earth; they came here, bought cows, pigs, hens from the whites.
Kã'ñã'_jiñãra je tsõ-ka ji kã' kërwa blali inga sa sa tsõ ji ska-ra jie-wa beteu ji ska-ra jeska (_) jie-wa të baga tũã' kuchi tũã' kabayu tũã' óshkoro tũã' je rö sikwa-wa ĩã
There were no roads, no electricity; it was all dark. The Ceibo River was the way we see it now.
Ka ñala ta ka lus se'i ta pa Kã' rö katuir ye ebö Bikis blali sa të sũẽ-gẽ (_) gepi
The elders say that there was no nice road and there were lots of weird beings who made us lose the way.
Sigeglö-wa të í page jiebi jeska ra ka ñala ta bá shkö-glö Tãĩ bichi sisulo të se je ñala se je ñala shëwẽ-gẽ se wö nã
When we were ill, there was no such thing as a hospital, as the whites call it.
Se döwö-gẽ-ra sikwa ktö' wa ka (_) ospital ta
Instead, there were the best healers who could cure all illnesses.
Jera jeska ra jawá-wa tsõ klõ-lẽ bá (_) döwe inga Je të pe döwö-gẽ (_)
Then, the Catholic church, it came, it baptized us.
Jera la Iglesia Katolika je beteu je të se (_) wöjoge-wa
Many people were so. They were not baptized.
The ancestors lived like that, blind.
The elders tell me that there was nothing in the savannah, like, say, bananas.
sigeglö-wa të yís ĩã í page jiebi ji ska kable Sök blali ra ka jirö kunã ta ka jirö kuna ĩã chomõ bi ke-le (_)
They came and there were two clans, the one called Julablöwa and the one called Kibeiglöwa;
Jie-wa (_) beteu-lo í ditsö' rö b-ol í ditsö' (_) kie Julablöwa (_) ditsö' (_) kie Kibeiglöwa
these clans came from afar, from our homeland, Talamanca.
je ditsö' (_) beteu kã' komĩ sa kã' ska Talamanka
Our families are there; our real roots are there.
Je-wa (_) jeska se gicha-wa tsõ jenẽ rö se je turi-wa chöglë
They also tell me that they married another clan there;
jeme yís í page-ite jiebi jeska í ñã jula gugá ditsö' (_) kwãwã (_)

and our clan came from there, so they say; there is a road in the mountain, in the Guanacaste area; it is the road that comes from our homeland and they also say that when we had to buy salt or sweets, we had to walk long distances because there was no road; there was nothing, as there is now.

Jenẽ ska sa ditséi beteu jie-wa të sa ĩã í page (_) ñala blali ñẽ kã'bata ñẽ Guanakaste shebe wa jamĩ wa mãũ Ñala blali je dajũ plaja sa kã' ska Jeme í she-ite sa (_) ĩã jiebi sa mi-gẽ (_) deye tũã' bi jirö blota tũã' gepi sa jenã shkö rö komĩ Ka ñala ta Ka jirö ta menẽbi sa të sũẽ-gẽ jir gepi
The elders used to live well;
they say that when they went to work, they would make chicha, but not like nowadays.
sigeglö-wa të í page jiebi jie-wa mĩ-gẽ-ra shkablö-ra jie-wa të di ble-gẽ ka rö jir í blegu-nã gepi kuna
They would make chicha for planting corn, beans, rice, and everything to eat and drink;
Jie-wa të di ble-gẽ rö kwö köglö kenĩ köglö arros köglö jirö bigögle ya-nã ñã-nã
The women would grind on stones to make the chicha.
í alaglö-wa mi-gẽ-nẽ je wö' jak inga kwö wö' di ble-nã
Nowadays we have forgotten all that.
Jiskara sa të jiskara sa të kable shëwãwã-ka
They told me that many years ago they lived well.
Jie-wa të she s-ĩã (_) kã'ñã'_jiñãra jie-wa senẽ-l bá
There were no fights, all the rivers were clean; people were clean;
Ka (_) ka ñarige ta Kable diglö tsõ rö siginã Sersö-wa tsõ siginã
there were no people like those from today, that is, ill-intentioned.
Ka yuru kuna ta ji (m) se je tsõ gepi jẽr sluí ta ebö
They also tell us that when children were born, the women would not fuck around;
Jeme sa ĩã í page-ite jiebi jie-wa yabla dö-gẽ-ra alaglö-wa bi ra jie-wa ka mĩ kuna se klinama yekwenama tsõ jãrga kuna
they would bear the children in our village.
Jie-wa yabla bötö-gẽ rö ji se je kẽĩ jãrga
They would build houses far away with banana and brar leaves, and there they would give birth to their children.
Se je male mĩ-gẽ jũ yuwö kã' komĩ chomõ kö' wa (_) brar kö' wa Jeska yabla bötö-gẽ í wa
They had to be cured; as they whites say, I’d say, they had to wait for three times during two weeks. Then they would go back home.
Jeska í jenã jula bötsö jeska í kianã sikwa ktö' wa she yís të ra jeska í kianã' í (_) (_) begetsö-pa í (_) kiksö-pa mãñãt-öbö (_) dögãũ kinse dia bi Jeskara í bötö-gẽ jũ ga
The elders say that long ago our first ancestors came to Ujarraz; they worked a lot; and many of them passed away; some are buried, so they say, and they tell it very well.

Jebi sigeglö-wa të í page kã'ñã'_jiñã se je gicha-wa se je ksei sögötö-wa-ra ji wa de (r) de-le jiska Ujarras ka rö jir sa të jie-wa (r) (_) jie-wa shkãblá tãĩ mẽnẽle ka sökönãĩã mẽnẽle tsõ-ka (m) ble-le söpök jãrga Jebi jie-wa të í page jie-wa të page bá
If you want to know more, ask the elders, the ones with gray hair; they are the best story-tellers. They suffered many illnesses;
Bas wã í kik (r) kĩksa-gle (_) bas wã í kĩ kianá ksen-ã-nẽ bas mĩ í chagö sigeglö-wa tsõ-ka tsãgũ súrrú jie-wa nẽ të bá í wa page Jira ka se kuna ĩã döe yunaga tãĩ jie-wa (_) inga (m) (_)
today’s illnesses send the elders to heaven, where they come from.
Ji döe tsõ je të se sigeglö-wa patk-erá-ka Surá kã' ska mãĩ í beteũ ska
if there is anything else to ask, you should ask the elders.
jirö kianá ĩã wöchagá-nã ĩã sigeglö-wa nẽ chagö-glö (_)
They, who lived long ago, know better, not like us, young people, who also know the history but the elders know it much better.

Jera (_) jie-wa senã kã'ñã'_jiñã jera jie-wa wã í jũñer bá ka rö se je datsẽ dulagle-wa Sa wãlé í jũñer böítsãnã sa të sigeglö-wa kẽĩ gugá (_) (_) tãĩ ra atara í gicha böítsãnã í siwã' jũñẽr böitsãnã je rö sigeglö-wa ka
The elders have already fought evil.
(_) Je ñã bele-ka bichi ra sha-bla yís të
Jenẽ wã í gicha jũñer böítsãnã
You should ask them and listen to them.
Jera jenẽ (_) wöchagẽ-wẽ bas të (m) Je kẽĩse kable bas të
That is all I can tell you.
